description.text:
I had the need for different nut mounts for my leadscrews on my custom D-bot.
The D-bot nut mounts doesn't align with the motor mounts if they are mounted "on the same vertical surface". I.E. if both nut mount and motor mount have same z rotation.

I designed new mounts that would align with my 3-leadscrew design using the remixed motor mounts from original D-bot: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2401504
According to my measurements it's 21mm from center of leadscrew to edge of aluminum extrusion with the D-bot motor mounts. Theese nut mounts are designed with this measurement and using M5 screws for mounting to extrusions.
There's no "groves" protruding to accommodate both V-Slot and T-Slot profiles.

There are 5 different nut mounts:
LeadScrewNutMount - Same design as original D-Bot, 50mm wide, but 21mm from nut center to the side that mounts to aluminum extrusion
LeadScrewNutMountThin - 36mm wide version of above
LeadScrewNutMountThin_corner-asym - 36x50mm wide corner nut mount, 21mm from nut center to either mounting side
LeadScrewNutMount_corner-sym - 50x50mm wide corner nut mount, 21mm from nut center to either mounting side
LeadScrewNutMount_corner-asym - Same as above but 21mm/16,2mm from nut center to mounting sides

Onlye tested the regular and thin mount, none of the corner pieces tested. Let me know what you think.

description.text:
Do you wanna build a snowflaaaake?

Well, BlocksCAD turns out to be a lot of fun! For the snowflake contest, I wanted something a bit more dynamic than just a shape, without losing sight of the original snowflake idea... so I added posability!
 

Ball Joint Fun

As is hopefully obvious in the photos, each snowflake arm has a series of ball joints, designed to allow rotation around the axis of that arm. So, the arm can be twisted and shaped as desired! The shape of the ball joint should prevent any undue movement in other directions, though, to avoid the shape collapsing! Also, the rotating parts are symmetrical across the axis of rotation, so that things remain balanced, and gravity can't mess up your designs.

 

About Those Colours...

You'll notice that my print has some nifty colour things going on! Nothing too tricky, though, just a filament change on four different occasions so that a white outer encloses a light blue inner and a dark blue core, for a fancy icy look! An alternative might be to just change colours half-way through, then spin alternating sections around for a cool multicolour effect.

 

The Code, and Test Printing

The BlocksCAD code is attached, and has a reasonable amount of comments stored against the blocks themselves. Also, there's an image uploaded here that has some annotations, too.

What is useful to know, though, is that there are a few parameters at the top of the code that can be helpful when testing the ball joints on your specific printer. After all, you don't want to print the whole design only to find that the joints are fused solid! The important settings are the number of arms and segments per arm (set those to 1 and 2, respectively, for a test setup), and the flag to omit the "whiskers".

Oh, and the gap parameter that controls the tolerance for the ball joint, that's important too :)

 

Parting words

I hadn't encountered a code-based modelling package that was aimed at students before, and I was concerned that it would be somewhat limiting. Really, though, there was nothing it wouldn't do, and hidden behind the colourful blocks are some pretty useful features for structuring code. I really like the passion and enthusiasm that's gone into making this stuff accessible and appealing!
(oh yeah, and the block clean-up feature, that is just awesome #hearteyes)

If you have a dual extruder printer, this might be a fun print job for you. Simply set the outer cylinder thingy to be printed in flexible or rubbery material, and the wheel to be printed in something more rigid. Or, hey, I'm not the boss of you... make the whole thing out of the rubbery stuff.. or ABS plastic... that could be fun too!

I'll tell ya this though, tires made of solid rubber are not suitable for driving on roads. This is true for real cars as well as RC. Print this set not at 100%. If you can do the wheels at 100%, and the tires at less, then that would be awesome. My software doesn't let me do that, so I went with 75% for good wheel strength and some tire compliance. I suspect that the tires should actually be made with 15% infill or less if possible though.

Oh, why is it that this is taking me 50-something hours? I was probably too meek with the print speed in order to guarantee the TPU stuff would work. You can probably print this much faster. I'm doing 10mm/second, but I suspect I could do twice that.

description.text:
I have seen a couple of other peoples implementation of adding a model of their printer to Simplify3D software. I liked the idea so I tried it and here are my build plate models.

MacOS Prep:

• Download the STL on this page
• Open a Mac Finder window and select "View > Show View Options" from the menu
• Click the "Show Library Folder" checkbox
• Go to /Users//Library/Application Support/Simplify3d/S3d-Software/
• Place a copy of the STL there

To install the STL model in Simplify3d:

• In Simplify3D, select "Simplify3D > Preferences... > Machine" and "Add" the STL in the "Printer Models" section
• Click "OK"

...and there you have it, a PrintrBot Simple Metal build plate model in Simplify3D. The print head is located at the 0,0,0 PrintrBot Simple Metal location for a 150x150x150mm print area.

I have included three (3) different versions as well as the STEP files so they can be modified.

If you have a PC or run into trouble, this page has all the information you need in the comments to get this working: https://forum.simplify3d.com/viewtopic.php?f=8&t=2356&p=12342#p12342

There are three versions of the frame mount for M4, M5 and M6 holes, choose the one that you require.

Tap a M4 thread into the bearing holder
Tap M3 threads into the Motor mount and the frame mount
You need to fit the frame mount onto the motor first, then follow the video for the assembly order.

I have been using it on my Hypercube for almost 2 months now with no problems. It won’t work well with flexible filaments though.

Nema 17 geared stepper motor

title: The Duck - Filament Dust Filter Clip v2

description.text:
Happy new year, 2018!

The filament dust filter clip has proven to be a very useful accessory. I've printed one clip for each spool I own using the spool's filament. So, now I have many of them printed successfully with several materials (PLA, ABS, PETG, wood).

I recently bought a couple of new filament spools and I decided that it is the time to add some improvements to the original design. The new design is more compact and requires less post-printing processing.

First of all, the clip and the filter shell are now a single part. Initially, I designed them as two separate parts that should be clipped together. I had in mind to design and print different clips to match the different spool shapes. But the initial design was proven to fit to every spool I own (Prusa, Filamentum, Prima Select, ...).

Second, the size of the filter shell is now smaller. I found that even a small piece of sponge is more than enough to clean and hold the dust collected after months of usage.

Third, the filter shell and the cap edges are now chamfered, so the cap can be placed easier to the filter shell.

Finally, I added a small notch, so it is now easier to open the filter sponge chamber.

I hope you enjoy it!

Prusa Mk2

Supports:

Filament: PLA 1.75mm
Layer height: 0.2mm
Perimeters: 2
Solid layers (Bottom/Top): 2
Infill density: 0%

Filament Auto cooling setting: Disabled (to print faster)

The printing completed in 13 minutes (thanks to Linear advance feature) and it consumed 60cm of 1.75mm PLA.

Cut a small piece of sponge, put it in the cap, pass the filament through it and finally close the filter.

Your Duck filament dust filter clip is ready to collect tones of dust per month!

title: Sculpto Printwall
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
THIS IS NOT MEANT TO BE PRINTED ALONE

This is a helper to make other prints successful! Download the .stl file and use a program like Slic3r or Tinkercad to combine it with other prints.

Many Sculpto users experience "lifting" with their prints, where the print let's go of the buildplate on the edge closest to the edge of the buildplate. Examples of this are in the pictures.

To solve this issue, or at least minimize it, combine your prints with this printwall. It adds a 199mm diameter, 0.05mm high, ring to your print. This is the maximum size Sculpto can handle and lets you position the prints further away from the edge of the buildplate.

The printwall can also be used to position prints on the buildplate, for example, if you have issues with y-calibration and want to avoid the center of the plate, add the printwall to your print and Sculpto will position your print parts exactly where you want them on the buildplate, as shown on the thumbnail picture, instead of printing them as close to the start point as possible.

Other tips to solve the lifting problem includes:

  • calibrate the y axis closer to the plate
  • clean the build plate with rubbing alchol
  • make sure there is no draft and avoid temperature changes in the room

Using the printwall has no effect on print time or the amount of material used. The wall is only 0.05mm high which the Sculpto cloud slicer ignores. No ring is printed.

description.header: What I could have done better
description.text:
Two things would have made this a better project: making the sections interlock, and separating out the buildings by size for better printing.

The pieces all fit together fine, but they are easily bumped out of place. If they were interlocking, I wouldn't have that problem.

A couple of the taller buildings got a little gooey when printing the tops because the layers didn't have sufficient time to cool and solidify before the next layer started printing. I should have extracted the taller buildings and printed them all together in one print job to resolve this problem.

Assembly

I'll write an instructable with pictures on how to put it together soon. Just this much for now:

You'll need per connector pair:

  • 2x Bottom part (3D printed)
  • 1x Top male and 1x Top female part (3D printed)
  • 4x cylinder/ring magnets with outer Ø10, inner Ø5mm and a height of 4mm. You can get them for ~40cents/piece. ¹
  • 4x Metal Eyelets with hole Ø5mm and outer Ø of ~10mm. You can get them for <5€/100pieces. ²
  • Some length of two-phase wire.
  • A few pieces of hard (non-flexible) single-strand blank wire.
  • A soldering iron and/or a spot welder.

Sand the eyelets on the inside and the top a bit. Then solder or spot weld the hard blank wire piece on the inside so it sticks out on the bottom. Put the magnets in the printed parts (with the poles alternating, so that you cannot accidentally connect it wrong way around). Then slide in the prepared eyelets. Add a drop of superglue to secure in place. Solder one strand of the cable to one of the pieces of the previously connected wires each. Finally have the wire go through the ring in the bottom part and glue it (2-3 tiny drops of superglue) to the top. Use the female side for the source (solar panel, battery, transformer, ...) and the male one for the drain (laptop, phone, ...).

There is one smaller issue: the ring on the male part will likely break off after some use. This makes it less slide off more easily, but you can still not connect it the wrong way around or have an accidental short-circuit.

This is a small foldable keychain designed to hold 1 or 2 sections of 9mm blade from a classic box-cutter (snap-off blades).

I wanted something that could cut open post packages and small ropes and fit in my pocket safely so I made this one in solidworks, took me 7 prototypes before finding "the one".

EDIT : I added a new way to insert the blade, it's way better ! The blade was sometimes getting out of her socket, so I redesigned it, now you insert the blade front behind and it locks into place, plus the blade is now on a corner which is way easier to open packages ! The new file for the inside is : 6_int_better.stl

Features :
There is a little protrusion so you can open it with one handed easily between your index and thumb.
It's small, ~3cmx2cm folded !
You can put it on a keyring.
It's supposed to be a tight fit so it shouldn't open on itself in your pocket (nor the blade should come loose). If it does because your printer doesn't have the same tolerances as mine, try heating the sheath a bit with a lighter (2sec) and press gently on the sides, it should tighten the fit.

Printing :
The first file should be sufficient for most printers, put supports underneath but not inside the model (I've included a screenshot of Cura so you'll have an idea).
You can also try the print-in-place version for added strength on the hinge but it's a trickier print. Finally you can print both pieces separately in whatever orientation you chose depending on your printer settings.
If you have any troubles, the easiest way to do it is to print the 4_ext flat on it's side with internal supports, and the 5_int in same way but with supports only underneath.
I should warn this is made for a 0.4mm nozzle, I don't know if the tolerances are okay for a bigger nozzle. I've included the Solidworks files if you want to tweak it.

For a while now, I've been wanting to upgrade my Printrbot Simple Metal with a heated bed. I've been hesitant to buy Printrbot's official upgrade kit, due to the $125 price tag. I ended up buying this $18 (including shipping) heater, and sticking it to the bottom of the printer's bed. Here are some pictures of it. The basic steps I followed to hook it up are below:

• remove the 4 screws holding the bed onto the printer.
  • remove the 2 screws holding the belt tensioner onto the bed.
  • lift the entire bed off the printer, and flip it over.
  • using a ruler and a pencil, on the bottom of the bed, mark an outline of the in middle where the heater should go.
  • peel off the backing from the double-sided adhesive on the heater, and stick it to the bottom of the bed. Make sure that the wires come out from one of the SIDES, NOT THE FRONT OR BACK!!
  • On the black plastic pieces that hold the bed onto the slider rods, there is a small cutout in the middle. Place the bed back onto the printer, making sure to route the wires through the cutout.
  • screw the bed back onto the printer, and reattach the belt tensioner.
  • flip over the printer, so that you can access the printrboard.
  • Strip the heater wires, and screw them into the screw terminals on the printrboard labeled "heatbed". There is a picture here that shows where everything needs to be hooked up.
  • plug the thermistor into it's appropriate connector, also shown here.

--NOTE-- I am not sure exactly which type of connector is used for connecting the thermistor to the printrboard. I happened to have a few laying around, and one of them fit. If anyone knows what type the connector is, please let me know. I think it's a type of Molex connector

  • plug in the 350+ Watt ATX power supply to the printrboard. The power plug on the Printrboard is a PCIE connector, which all computer power supplies have.

  • You will need to make one small change in the firmware, to tell the printer what thermistor you are using. If you don't know how to edit and flash firmware, read this guide. There are also a ton of other huides for editing and flashing marlin firmware, so I don't think that I need to go into detail here. The Heater that I bought Came with an NTC 3950 thermistor built into the heater itself. You will need to follow these instructions to add support for the NTC 3950 Thermistor. After that, open up configuration.h, and change #define TEMP_SENSOR_BED to #define TEMP_SENSOR_BED 8
  • flash the firmware, and YOU'RE DONE! Now, why not test it out by printing Hagster's Simple Warp Test. (I've uploaded the warp test .stl file with this thing as well).

Here is an Imgur album I put together with some more instructions. If you still need any help, please leave a comment or PM me, and I will help you out.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The X60 Micro is designed to be a clean, professional looking all-in-one FPV micro quadcopter comparable to a TinyWhoop. It was designed around the SciSky flight controller, using 7mm motors and Hubsan style props, for a final dimension of 85mm diagonal. The FPV equipment fits entirely within the top lid portion, allowing easy replacement of only the lower frame in the event of damage. Small rubber bands are used to hold the battery to the bottom of the frame, with two tie-down points. A fitted carrying case with multiple tie-down points for batteries is also included.

The FPV portion is designed to fit a Boscam vtx and 600tvl micro camera, along with a micro voltage regulator and frequency switches.

Edits from V1
-Carrying case is made thicker with larger tie-downs in more places.
-Only part which needs support to print is the FPV lid.
-Tuned all thin walls to ensure proper infill with .4mm nozzle.
-Added tops to motor pods to ensure they all stay at the proper height and don't wobble.
-Removed frame weight by making arms hollow and reducing thickness in strategic places.

Assembly

Besides electronics, motors, and props, the only additional supplies you will need are two screws and some servo tape for assembly. The diameter of the screw should be around 2mm or slightly larger, and around 6mm long.

Servo-tape the SciSky inside the frame's compartment. Servo tape the VTX to the inside of the top-plate, add 5v step-up inside the top hump, and route wires through to the camera mount. A hole is provided for a 3mm antenna tube. The only wires needed to connect the top and bottom halves of the frame are power. Examples of wiring are included in photos.

I highly recommend using Syma X5C-1 7mm motors. They can be had very cheap on Amazon and are very fast if you get one spec'ed the same rpm as the OEM motors.

title: Office Chair Footrests (Herman Miller Mirra v1)

description.text:
These are footrests I designed for Herman Miller's Mirra version 1 chair legs.

The chair legs on the first version of the Mirra chair -- which is the one I've happily been using for about 10 years now -- have curved legs which aren't comfortable to rest your feet on.

NOTE: Herman Miller recently came out with version 2 of their Mirra chair. One of the changes they made was to flatten the tops of the chair legs. I don't have a v2 Mirra on which to test, but I'm going to guess that these footrests will not be stable on a v2 Mirra.

Printer:

Monoprice Select Mini v2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.175

Infill:

40

Notes:

All the pieces print better with a zero-offset brim at the base. This is especially necessary for the straps, which print vertically.

I would also recommend that you print the straps with 100% infill because otherwise they are liable to break. The base/footrest itself can be printed at around 40% infill and still be rigid and stable.

Designed in Sketchup (but don't recommend)

To design these parts, I used Sketchup, though I would not use Sketchup again. While Sketchup is a great tool in a lot of ways, it has some really annoying drawbacks.

One big problem with Sketchup is that it's very difficult to create completely sealed/solid models suitable for 3D printing. Cura didn't complain about the models I was producing, though there were some weird artifacts. After upgrading to Simplify3D as my slicer, I saw lots of issues with my model meshes. I tried fixing them in Sketchup, but that was a nearly impossible task -- there's no easy way to fix or even find unclosed surfaces and missing egdes. Ultimately, I fixed the meshes by using Netfabb's online mesh repair tool (https://service.netfabb.com/login.php)

Also, when designing in millimeters in Sketchup, the smallest adjustment you can make is 1 millimeter. That's fine if you're designing a large object where 1mm is a reasonable resolution. That limitation is not so great when you need to design in sub-millimeter increments, as was the case with the footrests.

In order to get around this problem, I scaled up my models by 10 times -- meaning 1mm became 10mm in the new model. That allowed me to make changes on the large model that when scaled down again for output would result in fractional millimeter sizes. For example, to create a feature that was supposed to be 2.5mm I made that feature 25mm in the scaled up model.

Once I was done working on the scaled up version of the model, I would make a copy, and scale it down to 10% of its original size, resulting in a correctly-sized model that was ready for export to STL.

There are three factors to consider when selecting a base.

1) The tile size. This will match between the tile and the base, such as 2x2 or 4x2.

2) What size basis do you want the tiles to be in. There are three choices:

  • 25mm - every square is 25mm on a side. This is compatible with Dwarven Forge. There is no need to scale the tile top with 25mm.
  • inch - every square is 1 inch (25.4 mm). This is compatible with Printable Scenery (OpenLOCK), DragonLOCK and HirstArts. Scale the tile top when you print it by 101.6% in the X and Y axes.
  • wyloch - every square is an inch and a quarter (31.75mm). This is compatible with hero's horde and wyloch tiles. Scale the tile top when you print it by 127% in the X and Y axes.

3) What connection system do you want to use. We offer 4 connectivity options:

  • Magnetic - uses 5mm spherical magnets. 1 each along the center of every square that is on the edge of the tile
  • Magnetic + OpenLOCK - uses 5mm spherical magnets. 1 each along the center of every square that is on the edge of the tile. Also has an OpenLOCK connector at the vertice between each square.
  • OpenLOCK - Has an OpenLOCK connector at the vertice between each square.
  • OpenLOCK Triplex - Has an OpenLOCK connector at the vertice between each square, and at the center of each square.

description.text:
I replaced the drivers for X and Y axis with SilentStepSticks from Watterott. They come with heat sinks that are higher than those on the stock driver modules inhibiting mounting the original top-blower again.

Since the top-blower was of not much use anyway (it's blocked by the bottom sheet metal which has no openings in place there) it was time to design this fan holder.

The fan holder can be mounted with the screws of the old metal holder, but I used the longer screws that held the old fan. The holder should also be glued onto the "ceiling" using double-sided tape to avoid vibrations.

You can use the old fan, or two silent ones (50x50x10 mm). If you want to mount two fans, you have to solder or use a Y-cable, of course. And your replacement fan must have mounting holes with 40mm distance (I've seen ones having 42 mm).

I ended up fixing the fans using those - um - silicon straps that were left-over from the Noctua fan I use as the nozzle cooler. That way no vibration is transferred to the chassis at all.

Note: The place for the M3 hex nut is designed with 5.5 mm distance which should be enough in theory. However, mine came out too small to actually insert an M3 nut.

I was recently introduced to the game of Right-Left-Center and decided to design my own dice. There are versions of the game where taking a drink is one of the 6 options as well as skipping a turn and no action. I originally made a single unit die that had the “R”, “L”, “C”, “O”, “O”, “O” molded in but the backgrounds would need to be painted to be able to read the die across the table. I then thought it would be even better to make a “blank” die and inserts that could be color coded and arranged in any desired order and possibly customize the die for other games.

I then made a hollow version of the blank die that makes the die lighter or easier to “load”, although since every player uses the same die, I don't see any reason to do so. I have not tried it yet, but sealing a couple of loose 10mm ball bearings inside the hollow die might be interesting.

I have included STL files for the original fixed die, the blank die, the hollow blank die and a number of insert panels including “R”, “L”, “C”, “O”, “X”, “D”, “1”, “2”, “3”, “4”, “5”, “6”, conventional “dots ” and blank. You can print the die and inserts in any colors that suit your use, but using different colors for each panel will make the die readable from across the table. There are a number of adhesives that can be used to glue the inserts to the die, but my favorite is Super Glue Fix-All Gel in a tube that I get at Dollar Tree.

The die is 1.5” (38.1mm) but can be scaled in your slicer as desired. The small die in the picture are scaled 80%, 50% and 33% I have included removable supports and pads on the hollow die to improve bed adhesion.

I came across these polyhedra in Professor Bonnie M. Stewart's wonderful book, Adventures Among the Toroids. They aren't toroidal, and he uses them as examples of a particular type of polyhedron that he doesn't discuss elsewhere in the book; nevertheless, I thought they were worth modeling. In Stewart's notation, the cuboctahedron is B4, and these two are B4,3 (with square sides removed) and B4,4 (triangle sides removed). They're otherwise known as an octahemioctahedron and a cubohemioctahedron. They share the property of having four hexagonal faces that cut each other, similar to the tetrahemihexahedron; like that shape, B4,4 is non-orientable. Interestingly, though, B4,3 is orientable. For both models it's easier to see the central hexagons if they're colored or painted after printing. March 20 update - I added an option to choose the plain B4 so you can print a set of all three shapes, along with its STL.

The models are customizable to choose which polyhedron is generated, the length of a side, the size of the fillet blocks and whether a hollow or solid side is down. I found that with this shape, the fillet blocks needed to be slightly larger than with the tetrahemihexahedron model; the default works for my printers. Note that as far as I can see the B4,3 model is printable without support only on a hollow side, and B4,4 only on a solid side. Both are likely to need fixup with Netfabb, Meshlab or the like before they can be sliced.  
The STL files are 30 mm on a side, rotated to print without support and fixed in Netfabb Cloud.

This is a remix of the smart effector Nimble mount by Zesty Technologies.

It includes a nut trap for the large nut holding the nut that secures the heatsink. This prevents it from loosening, as once the adaptor is installed it is practically impossible to get to it to tighen it.

This doesn't seem to affect the sensitivity of the smarteffector, but ensure the large nut fits nicely into the adaptor and is not very tight against it, as this might dampen the flex of the PCB and make the SE less sensitive. You also need to consider the orientation of the large nut to you heatsink when assembling the hotend into the SE.

title: Axis 6 for Moveo Modified Robot Arm with Openbuilds universal mount Plate

description.text:
This project takes labala's excellent 6th axis rotory joint for the moveo robot and allows it to be adapted to an Openbuilds 5mm universal mounting hub (http://openbuildspartstore.com/mounting-hub-5mm/). It also includes an adaptor plate to utilize the stock Moveo gripper until you can make a better one.

Required materials:
1 Openbuilds 5MM universal mounting hub
4 M5 10mm bolts
4 m3 heat set inserts (mcmaster carr https://www.mcmaster.com/#94180a331/=1axdlb8)
8 M3 nuts
8 8mm M3 bolts
4 10mm M3 bolts
4 8mm dia, 3mm wide 3mm dia hole bearings (MR83)
1 Moveo gripper kit and associated hardware

Instructions.

  1. Print the part face down (does not require support). After printing, use a 5mm drill or a reamer tool to remove the 1mm thick hole covering material in the M5 bolt recesses.
  2. Insert the MR83 3x8x3 bearings into their slots, and drop in 4 m3 nuts. They should go in with minimal resistance. Secure the bearings with the 4 M3 10mm bolts. Ensure the bearings still turn freely, adjust as needed.
  3. Install the openbuilds universal mounting hub on the end of the motor that will drive the 6th axis and test fit the 6th axis so the bearings ride on the face of the 5th axis housing properly to provide support. Secure the universal mounting hub using the set screws from the side then secure the 6th axis to it using the 4 M5 bolts from the front of the 6th axis. they thread into the universal mounting hub. They should be as close to flush with the surface of axis 6 as possible.
  4. insert the 4 heat set inserts into the 3d printed adaptor plate and let cool.
  5. Place 4 M3 nuts into the bottom of the 6th axis in 4 of the mounting holes that will line up with the adaptor plate. Use 4 m3 8mm bolts to secure the adaptor plate to the 6th axis
  6. Use 4 M3 8mm bolts to screw the Moveo gripper to the adaptor plate.

This should work with most of the other 5th axis bodies out there, as well as any other application where you need a supported rotating platform with hardpoints attached to a 5mm shaft.

description.text:
Small thing to replace antenna on a Fiat 500. I wanted to get rid of the antenna so my car cover would be easier to put on. I just used a random screw with the same thread. Surprisingly enough the radio still works fine.

When I have more time I plan on replacing the entire thing with a smaller, flatter cap but that requires accessing a nut under the roof liner.

The other hot end holders I have used take care to avoid touching the lower fins. If the nozzle drags at all it has plenty of leverage to move around.

This design grips the hot end as tightly as possible. From the thermal images I've seen of an e3d the heat at the lower fins isn't an issue for PLA. In practice this hasn't been an issue either. The trade off here is that if a print drags hard enough it can bend the heat break.

This also has insets for a fan on every side if you want to get crazy with cooling.

I decided to make a snowflake, but instead of making a normal, boring old snowflake, I decided to make one that's a little...cooler. I was also able to incorporate the example snowflake into one of the designs. ( In the pictures, there is one piece missing. I ended up having to scale it down a bit for my printer, so your hinges that you print will most likely be bigger and stronger, so they don't fall off.)

description.text:
This is a simple tool I imagined.  Having been a geometry teacher at the breakout of Geometry SketchPad I've been frustrated by the limitation to leverage this powerful tool for students who are visually impaired.  Triangle interdependence of angle and side measurements is an important concept that creates foundation for triginometry and higher level math.  
3 prints of this tool with a bolt and wing nut allows an individual to adjust sides and angle and using the tactile measurement guides along the edges a blind individual can gain immediate impact of their transformations.  More simply a person learns that they can not alter any given side or angle without loosening more than one wing nut!  
This is version 2.0.  I would love to see someone adapt the bolt hole to hold a magnet or pushpin and then a slider one could lock in the channel so that the tool would become a compass as well!  The foundation is there, but I'm just learning.

Modeled in Google sketchup, and modified with multiple prototypes.  This model was made on minimal settings, but I'm making it heavier as the student I work with will over tighten the wing nuts which stretches the channel apart.  I'm going to print a couple washers to address this and will drop additional files here as I find the right sizes.  
To print a heavier duty version you can layer two of the tools back to back with hex groove facing out.  I printed a version like this and found it more resilient.

This model solves a very specific problem for me, and I thought I'd share in case somebody else was looking for the same thing.

This is a small clip that will hold a cell phone over the navigation screen on a 2013 Subaru Crosstrek or Impreza. The clip fits snugly under the navigation unit, and the lip on the clip is just large enough to catch the edge of my Samsung Galaxy S8+ case, but not cover the screen. UPDATE: Version 2 offers more flexibility. Instead of using a threaded nut to hold the phone holder in place you can use rubber bands to apply the tension, but you can still add the nut for more security. I added more robust right and left grips that feel more comfortable. Just be sure to sand the edges.

I needed a simple, easily printable rig for my Samsung s6 and 8 that can be made with cheap hardware from any hardware store. I love the idea of Beastgrip, and maybe I will buy one in the future, but I had a few days off for Christmas and figured I'd challenge myself. Solving the mechanism to hold the phone securely was the most interesting challenge. I considered springs and bands, but I decided to use friction. The phone is simply held in place by squeezing the jaws together and tightening the knurled nut. My prototype was done in natural ABS, using steel 1/4" 20 all thread, but I added a little more personality with wood, and black PLA, and brass 1/4" 20 all thread. The lens holder will hold a 37mm filter ring that the Polaroid lens will screw in. It's not really designed for a non-centered lens, but can be modified to fit on. I will attach cold shoe, or Picatinny mounts to support a Mic and flash. Adding a tripod mount was never considered, but can possibly be done at a later date

description.text:
Like the motor boat http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:272132 I wanted to make another bigger boat. So I just scaled up my boat http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:204303 to about 200%. Only the transom is half as thick.
It can be printed in two parts: 162,5 mm (aft) and 163,5 mm (bow) height.
Additional it has now a impeller drive and rudder control.
The complete rudder control unit can be taken from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:272132
I tried to use my Roxxy BL-Outrunner which I already used for my plane http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:86982
But as you can see on the video, the boat is pretty overloaded with it. Only a little mistake is enough to turn it upside. So I had to go back to the little dc motor which makes it much more relaxing ;-)
http://youtu.be/UBQ-xlQTCDg
I used only a 2 cell battery because the impeller with only 2 mm hole was not printet exactly concentric. With higher speed it touches the housing. However, the impeller M5 runs perfectly even with the Roxxy BL-Outrunner.
For testing it I just bonded the two parts with tape ;-) Attention:
You will use it at your own risk!
Be aware that there will accrue unexpected high centifugal force if you run the impeller with high speed!!
If the blades have not a strong connection to the hub, the blades can pull out and become dangerous.
So be careful if you use a strong and high speed running motor like the Roxxy Outrunner that I used!
Here you can calculate the centrifugal force: http://www.kfz-tech.de/Formelsammlung/Fliehkraft.htm
And better choose flat water without waves and where you can go in - in worst case... ;-)

Update
MHarvey82 asked me to split the hull in three pieces.
So I made an alternate design and uploaded the files:
impeller boat bow 119 mm.stl
impeller boat middle 103 mm.stl
impeller boat aft 103 mm.stl
impeller boat interface front.stl
impeller boat interface back.stl
The bow is now 119 mm and the other two pieces are each 103 mm high to print. And of course there are two new interfaces. Printing
The best is, if you print it with spiral vase methode. Then you will get a neat surface without any noses from layer change. Hull
The hull is 3.0 mm thick.
I printed with layer hight: 0.3 mm and width: 0.6 mm.
Anyway, you have to print it hollow with one perimeter otherwise it will not fit inside the interface part to connect the bow to the aft.
I added a small base on aft to get more brim. I printed without heatbed and used 6 mm brim.
And yes, be very careful, if you reach the nose.
Reduce the temperature and speed by and by in small steps. Printing the Aft
The stern is 1.2 mm thick. That means you must take four 0.3 mm solid layers on bottom to get a complete solid stern.
The top (the connection to the bow) shall not have solid layers to stay hollow.
Slice3r don't add solid layers on top, how many ever you enter. But I don't know how other slicers work. Printing the bow
Here you shall not have solid layers, just a little brim. Interfaces
The interfaces are supposed to put them fifty-fifty in the gap of each hull part. In this way the the hull parts are aligned and easy to glue.
Before gluing you should mask the edges of the hulls with tape to keep them clean from glue. Impeller
Layer height: 0.3 mm, width: 0.5 mm, infill: 0.2, 2 perimeter, 3 solid layer on bottom and top Impeller housing
Layer height: 0.3 mm, width: 0.5 mm, infill: 0.2, 2 perimeter, 2 solid layer on bottom and top Drive
The small drive I used is a dc motor that tolerates even a 4 cells battery.
It has a diameter of 24 mm and a shaft of 2 mm.

description.text:
This is my version of the DSO138 oscilloscope case that eliminates the 9V power port, and uses the USB for power. By doing this, the oscilloscope becomes ultra portable that can be powered using a USB power bank!

To do this, I bought a MT3608 voltage step up circuit board to step up the 5V power from the USB to 9V, and solder the input and output cables to the correct pins on the DSO138 oscilloscope (see picture for the USB power connection). The 9V socket and the white 2-pin socket have been removed from the DSO138 circuit board to make room for the MT3608. Since the MT3608 board sticks out slightly from the top edge, and slightly higher than the LCD screen of the DSO138 board, the case is therefore, specifically designed to make room for the MT3608. (Note: I found that the new version of the MT3608 isn't as tall as the older version that I have, but a lot longer. I made a small change to my front cover's original design, but I have never tried this. Please download the appropriate STL file for your need.) Also, I put a masking tape under the MT3608 as an insulator to separate the 2 circuit boards.

There are 3 clamps to hold the top and bottom of the case together. By doing this, I can quickly remove the clips, open the case and get access to the internal of the oscilloscope. Also, if you don't like the stands that I made, you can always create ones that fit your needs. The dimensions are in the picture, and the thickness of the case is 0.92 inches (All units in picture are in inches).
Case is designed in SolidWorks 2014
